Infielders move through the fielding lanes to make a variety of plays. The best throwers are the most versatile, allowing their direction and posture to dictate how the throw the ball. The direction of the ball will often times decide how the fielder throws the ball.

HEADS UP PLAY BY THE CATCHER, plus good execution of the rundown by the infielders. As a defensive player in the rundown you want to keep a few things in mind. 

•As few throws as possible
•Show your teammate the ball early, 
•Throw a dart when executing the throw
•Stay on same side of runner as your teammate. Avoid throwing across the runner 
•SPRINT at the runner!! If the base runner is running looking over their shoulder, go get them yourself. As soon as they turn their head it’s often times a good time to tag (if close enough) or complete the throw.
•Communicate when you want your teammate to make the throw. A simple “now” call works. 
•Cut down the distance between you & the runner by coming off the base a few steps. Try not to come too far off. 
•Avoid chasing runner to lead base.

The “heel - toe” landing with the left foot (glove foot) is a natural move if you’re moving in balance. Think about how your strikes the ground when you walk with regular pace .. heel - toe.

As infielders we want to below the ball. We do that by “loading” into the right leg as we begin to descend into catch. We will see an on time , heel - toe landing if we stay loaded in that right leg as we catch & the left foot lands. Ideally, the left foot will begin to set direction to throw as it lands to create direction targets to 🎯 

Starting toe up on station drills is a great way to help infielders feel the momentum through catch & not get stuck on catch.
